{"title_page": "Freedom Socialist Party", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Freedom Socialist Party\n| logo = Freedom Socialist Party logo (visible).png\n| caption = Logo of the Freedom Socialist Party\n| chairman = [[Doug Barnes]]\n| colorcode = Red\n| foundation = {{Start date|1966}}\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Revolutionary integrationism]]<br>[[Revolutionary socialism]]<br>[[Socialist feminism]]<br>[[Trotskyism]]\n| position = [[Far-left]]\n| international = [[Committee for Revolutionary International Regroupment]] (CRIR)\n| newspaper = ''The Freedom Socialist''\n| headquarters = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.socialism.com}}\n| seats1_title = [[United States Senate|Seats in the Senate]]\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|0|100|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats2_title = [[United States House of Representatives|Seats in the House]]\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|0|435|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats3_title = [[Governor (United States)|Governorships]]\n| seats3 = {{composition bar|0|50|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats4_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Upper House Seats]]\n| seats4 = {{composition bar|0|1972|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats5_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Lower House Seats]]\n| seats5 = {{composition bar|0|5411|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats6_title = Other elected offices\n| seats6 = {{composition bar|0|5411|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| country = United States\n}}\n{{American socialism |Modern parties}}\n\nThe '''Freedom Socialist Party''' is a far-left [[Socialism|socialist]] political party with a [[Socialist feminism|revolutionary feminist]] philosophy that emerged from a split in the [[Socialist Workers Party (United States)|United States Socialist Workers Party]] in 1966.<ref name=\"Alexander\">Alexander, Robert. ''International Trotskyism, 1929-1985: A Documented Analysis of the Movement''. Duke University Press, 1991, p. 936.</ref> The party views the struggles of women and minorities as part of the struggle of the working class. The party's [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] branch, with support from individuals in other cities, split off from the SWP over what it described as the SWP's entrenched [[opportunism]] and undemocratic methods. The party has branches in the [[United States]], as well as [[Australia]], [[Canada]], [[England]], [[Germany]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Where We Are |url=https://socialism.com/where-we-are/ |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=Freedom Socialist Party}}</ref> The current National Secretary of the FSP is Doug Barnes.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Seattle - Columbia City - New Freeway Hall 01.jpg|thumb|left|New Freeway Hall, [[Columbia City, Seattle, Washington]], party headquarters.]]\nThe immediate forerunner of the FSP was the Kirk-Kaye tendency within the Socialist Workers Part (SWP), led by Dick Fraser (Kirk) and [[Clara Fraser]] (Kaye) who were at the time husband and wife.<ref name=Sheppard>{{cite book |last=Sheppard|first=Barry|title=The Party: The Socialist Workers Party, 1960-1988, Volume 1|year=2005|publisher=Resistance Books|page=104}}</ref> At the time Richard Fraser was seen as the central leader of the tendency due to his development of the theory of revolutionary integrationism. In addition to their distinctive position on civil rights, derived from said theory of revolutionary integrationism, the tendency also took a position that was more sympathetic to China than was the norm in the SWP, in part this being due to the alliance between the Kirk-Kaye tendency and the loser tendency of Arne Swabeck and Frank Glass.\n\nPolitical differences, as articulated by the soon-to-become FSP, included what was characterized as the SWP's uncritical support of the black nationalist views of [[Malcolm X]], SWP's orientation toward the [[labor aristocracy]], its opportunism in the [[Opposition to the Vietnam War|anti-Vietnam War movement]], and its dismissive attitude toward the emerging [[feminist movement]]. The nascent FSP advocated the [[social class|class]] [[Solidarity (sociology)|solidarity]] of [[African-American|black]] and [[White people|white]] workers, called for a greatly expanded understanding of and attention to [[socialist feminism|women's emancipation]], and urged the [[anti-war]] movement to support the socialist, [[anti-colonialism|anti-colonial]] aims of the [[August Revolution|Vietnamese Revolution]].\n\nThe FSP became a pole of attraction for Seattle leftists opposed to the SWP's internal politics and established a home at Freeway Hall.<ref name=Crowley>{{cite book |last=Crowley|first=Walt|title=Rites of Passage: A Memoir of the Sixties in Seattle|year=2010|publisher=University of Washington Press|pages=21\u201322}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Winslow|first=Barbara|title=The Feminist Memoir Project: Voices from Women's Liberation|year=2007|pages=227, 230\u2013231, 235\u2013236|chapter=Primary and Secondary Contradictions in Seattle: 1967-1969|editor=Rachel Blau DuPlessis, Ann Barr Snitow}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=McKay|first=Ian|title=Rebels, Reds, Radicals: Rethinking Canada's Left History|year=2005|publisher=Between the Lines|page=242}}</ref>  The party formed [[Radical Women]] with the dual goal of building a revolutionary socialist feminist organization and teaching women the organizational and leadership skills they were often denied in male-dominated organizations.<ref name=NotableWomen>{{cite book |last=James|first=Edward T., Janet Wilson James, Paul S. Boyer|title=Notable American Women: A Biographical Dictionary, Volume 5|publisher=Harvard University Press|page=414}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\n[[File:Newfsmastheadtr.png|thumb|150px|Former logo]]\nThe FSP is politically [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]]. FSP leaders [[Clara Fraser]] (1923\u20131998) and Gloria Martin (1916\u20131995) built on the socialist analysis of women's [[oppression]] to create a [[Leninist]] party that is \"socialist-feminist\" in ideology and practice.<ref name=Love>{{cite book|last=Love|first=Barbara J.|title=Feminists Who Changed America, 1963-1975|url=https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=University of Illinois Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love/page/158 158]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ware|first=Susan|title=Notable American Women: A Biographical Dictionary, Volume 5: Completing the Twentieth Century|year=2005|publisher=Harvard University Press|pages=414\u2013415|author2=Stacy Braukman|chapter=Martin, Gloria}}</ref> The party views the liberation struggles of women, [[person of color|people of color]] and [[sexual minority|sexual minorities]] (such as [[homosexuality|gay people]]) as intrinsic to [[working class]] [[revolt]], and it looks to these specially-oppressed sectors of society to provide revolutionary leadership. Women comprise a predominant part of the party leadership. Overall, membership is very diverse and is composed of all genders and races. The party characterizes its ''National Comrades of Color Caucus'' as offering the party's diverse ranks of people of color an opportunity to work together as a team to grow as leaders and provide direction for the party's work in people of color movements.\n\n== Strategy ==\nThe party has frequently supported [[united front]] efforts on a number of issues and often helps other socialist groups get on the ballot, while simultaneously running its own candidates for office.\n\nThe United Front Against Fascism (UFAF)\u2014founded by the FSP, but also including a broad coalition of the [[left-wing politics|Left]], the [[LGBT]] community, [[trade union|labor unionists]], [[feminism|feminists]], [[people of color]], [[Jew]]s, and [[civil liberties|civil libertarians]]\u2014took the lead in mobilizing against [[neo-Nazism|neo-Nazis]] in the [[Pacific Northwest]] in the 1980s and 90s.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kubelbeck|first=Amy|title=Groups Of Gays Protest Picnic|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19900804&slug=1086045|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=Aug 4, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lacitis|first=Erik|title=An Ax To Grind -- When It Comes To Skinheads And Nazis, Loggers, Gays Unite|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910716&slug=1294655|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=1991-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Angelos|first=Constantine|title=Rice, Citizens Groups Join To Declare Seattle Won't Tolerate Hate Crimes|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19900519&slug=1072597|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=1990-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gough|first=William|title=A Gathering Of Neo-Nazis -- Encampment Draws Protest|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19911208&slug=1321657|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=Dec 8, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reang|first=Putsata|title=Supremacist Guilty In Klan Scuffle -- Federal Way Man Broke Free- Lancer's Camera|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19961002&slug=2352224|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=Oct 2, 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wilcox|first=Laird|title=The Cultic Milieu|year=2002|publisher=Rowman Altamira|pages=334\u2013335|editor=Jeffrey S. Kaplan, Hel\u00e9ne L\u00f6\u00f6w|chapter=Who Watches the Watchmen?}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seattle Freeway Hall.jpg|thumb|Freeway Hall in [[Seattle]]'s [[Northlake, Seattle, Washington|Northlake]] neighborhood was for many years the FSP headquarters.]]\nThe party has branches in a number of U.S. cities, as well as one in [[Melbourne, Australia]]. The ''Freedom Socialist'' newspaper is produced six times a year. Red Letter Press publishes books and pamphlets for the party. The FSP is affiliated with [[Radical Women]], which is an [[Autonomous entity|autonomous]] socialist feminist organization.\nIn 2003, Red Letter Press and its managing editor, Helen Gilbert, were the target of a complaint to the [[Federal Election Commission]] by the campaign committee of perennial presidential candidate [[Lyndon LaRouche]]. LaRouche alleged that Gilbert and the FSP publishing house, which had issued a pamphlet by Gilbert critical of LaRouche's ideology and political history,<ref>Helen Gilbert, [http://www.redletterpress.org/redreaders.html#larouche \"Lyndon Larouche: Fascism Restyled for the New Millennium\"], Redletterpress.org</ref> were in violation of campaign finance laws. The FEC found LaRouche's complaint to be without merit and dismissed it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/press/press2004/20041104mur.html|work=[[Federal Election Commission]]|title=COMPLIANCE CASE MADE PUBLIC|date=November 4, 2004|access-date=August 24, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831114409/http://fec.gov/press/press2004/20041104mur.html|archivedate=August 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Jordana Sardo, party organizer in Portland, Oregon, ran for the [[Oregon House of Representatives]] in Oregon's 45th House district, earning 8.74% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=97680%7celections |title=OR State House 45 Race - Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |access-date=2016-01-29}}</ref> Other FSP campaigns have been run in New York, Washington state, and California.<ref>Linda Averill, Freedom Socialist, October 1998, [http://www.socialism.com/drupal-6.8/?q=node/1224 \"Enthusiastic support puts radicals on the ballot in four states\"]</ref>\n\nIn [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]], the party ran a [[write-in]] presidential campaign with candidates [[Stephen Durham]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. president]] and Christina L\u00f3pez for [[Vice President of the United States|vice-president]].<ref>[http://votesocialism.com Durham/Lopez campaign website], Votesocialism.com</ref><ref>Ballot Access News, January 29, 2012, [http://www.ballot-access.org/2012/01/29/freedom-socialist-party-nominates-its-first-national-ticket/ \"Freedom Socialist Party Nominates its First National Ticket\"].</ref> The ticket received 117 votes nationwide.<ref>The Green Papers [http://www.thegreenpapers.com/G12/President-Details.phtml?n=DURHAM,STEPHENGAYLORD \"Votes for Stephen Gaylord Durham\"].</ref><ref>Ballot Access News [http://www.ballot-access.org/2012/12/31/new-york-state-posts-final-2012-election-returns-tally-presidential-vote-increases-by-400332-votes/ \"New York State Posts Final 2012 Election Returns Tally; Presidential Vote Increases by 400,332 Votes\"].</ref> Eight states do not permit write-in candidates, 32 require prior registration to be an official write-in, and many do not report write-ins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/2016-election/write-in-votes/|title=\"Planning to write in Paul Ryan or Bernie Sanders? It won\u2019t count in most states.\"|website=Washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 election, FSP critically endorsed [[Jeff Mackler]] of [[Socialist Action (United States)|Socialist Action]] for president.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://socialism.com/statement/this-year-of-the-detestable-election-exercise-your-democratic-rights-with-a-protest-vote/|title=This Year of the Detestable Election, exercise your democratic rights with a protest vote!|date=October 2016|website=Socialism.com|access-date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the party announced that member [[Steve Hoffman (activist)|Steve Hoffman]] would seek to petition onto the ballot for [[United States Senate election in Washington, 2018|United States Senate]] against incumbent Democrat [[Maria Cantwell]]. Hoffman got 7,390 votes (0,4%) and did not advance to the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialism.com/fs-article/union-stalwart-steve-hoffman-runs-us-senate-washington-state-freedom-socialist-party-campaign/|title=Union stalwart and socialist feminist Steve Hoffman runs for U.S. Senate|website=Freedom Socialist Party|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Socialism and Liberty Party]]\n* [[Party for Socialism and Liberation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.socialism.com/drupal-6.8/ Freedom Socialist Party]\n*[http://www.RedLetterPress.org Red Letter Press]\n*[http://www.RadicalWomen.org Radical Women]\n\n===Archives===\n*[http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=FreedomSocialistPartySeattleBranch1545.xml Freedom Socialist Party Seattle Branch Records.] 1984-1992. 3.14 cubic feet.\n*[http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=WindofferMelba1798.xml Melba Windoffer Papers.] 1933-1990. 7.42 cubic feet (8 boxes). Contains records from Windoffer's service with the Freedom Socialist Party.\n{{WashingtonPoliticalParties}}\n{{United States state and local political parties}}\n{{United States political parties}}\n{{Communist parties in the United States}}\n{{Australian socialist groups}}\n[[Category:Freedom Socialist Party| ]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political parties in the United States]]\n[[Category:1966 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Freedom Socialist Party\n| logo = Freedom Socialist Party logo (visible).png\n| caption = Logo of the Freedom Socialist Party\n| chairman = [[Doug Barnes]]\n| colorcode = Red\n| foundation = {{Start date|1966}}\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Revolutionary socialism]]<br>[[Socialist feminism]]<br>[[Trotskyism]]\n| position = [[Far-left]]\n| international = [[Committee for Revolutionary International Regroupment]] (CRIR)\n| newspaper = ''The Freedom Socialist''\n| headquarters = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.socialism.com}}\n| seats1_title = [[United States Senate|Seats in the Senate]]\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|0|100|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats2_title = [[United States House of Representatives|Seats in the House]]\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|0|435|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats3_title = [[Governor (United States)|Governorships]]\n| seats3 = {{composition bar|0|50|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats4_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Upper House Seats]]\n| seats4 = {{composition bar|0|1972|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats5_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Lower House Seats]]\n| seats5 = {{composition bar|0|5411|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| seats6_title = Other elected offices\n| seats6 = {{composition bar|0|5411|hex=#0BDA51}}\n| country = United States\n}}\n{{American socialism |Modern parties}}\n\nThe '''Freedom Socialist Party''' is a far-left [[Socialism|socialist]] political party with a [[Socialist feminism|revolutionary feminist]] philosophy that emerged from a split in the [[Socialist Workers Party (United States)|United States Socialist Workers Party]] in 1966.<ref name=\"Alexander\">Alexander, Robert. ''International Trotskyism, 1929-1985: A Documented Analysis of the Movement''. Duke University Press, 1991, p. 936.</ref> The party views the struggles of women and minorities as part of the struggle of the working class. The party's [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] branch, with support from individuals in other cities, split off from the SWP over what it described as the SWP's entrenched [[opportunism]] and undemocratic methods. The party has branches in the [[United States]], as well as [[Australia]], [[Canada]], [[England]], [[Germany]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Where We Are |url=https://socialism.com/where-we-are/ |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=Freedom Socialist Party}}</ref> The current National Secretary of the FSP is Doug Barnes.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Seattle - Columbia City - New Freeway Hall 01.jpg|thumb|left|New Freeway Hall, [[Columbia City, Seattle, Washington]], party headquarters.]]\nThe immediate forerunner of the FSP was the Kirk-Kaye tendency within the Socialist Workers Part (SWP), led by Dick Fraser (Kirk) and [[Clara Fraser]] (Kaye) who were at the time husband and wife.<ref name=Sheppard>{{cite book |last=Sheppard|first=Barry|title=The Party: The Socialist Workers Party, 1960-1988, Volume 1|year=2005|publisher=Resistance Books|page=104}}</ref> At the time Richard Fraser was seen as the central leader of the tendency due to his development of the theory of revolutionary integrationism. In addition to their distinctive position on civil rights, derived from said theory of revolutionary integrationism, the tendency also took a position that was more sympathetic to China than was the norm in the SWP, in part this being due to the alliance between the Kirk-Kaye tendency and the loser tendency of Arne Swabeck and Frank Glass.\n\nPolitical differences, as articulated by the soon-to-become FSP, included what was characterized as the SWP's uncritical support of the black nationalist views of [[Malcolm X]], SWP's orientation toward the [[labor aristocracy]], its opportunism in the [[Opposition to the Vietnam War|anti-Vietnam War movement]], and its dismissive attitude toward the emerging [[feminist movement]]. The nascent FSP advocated the [[social class|class]] [[Solidarity (sociology)|solidarity]] of [[African-American|black]] and [[White people|white]] workers, called for a greatly expanded understanding of and attention to [[socialist feminism|women's emancipation]], and urged the [[anti-war]] movement to support the socialist, [[anti-colonialism|anti-colonial]] aims of the [[August Revolution|Vietnamese Revolution]].\n\nThe FSP became a pole of attraction for Seattle leftists opposed to the SWP's internal politics and established a home at Freeway Hall.<ref name=Crowley>{{cite book |last=Crowley|first=Walt|title=Rites of Passage: A Memoir of the Sixties in Seattle|year=2010|publisher=University of Washington Press|pages=21\u201322}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Winslow|first=Barbara|title=The Feminist Memoir Project: Voices from Women's Liberation|year=2007|pages=227, 230\u2013231, 235\u2013236|chapter=Primary and Secondary Contradictions in Seattle: 1967-1969|editor=Rachel Blau DuPlessis, Ann Barr Snitow}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=McKay|first=Ian|title=Rebels, Reds, Radicals: Rethinking Canada's Left History|year=2005|publisher=Between the Lines|page=242}}</ref>  The party formed [[Radical Women]] with the dual goal of building a revolutionary socialist feminist organization and teaching women the organizational and leadership skills they were often denied in male-dominated organizations.<ref name=NotableWomen>{{cite book |last=James|first=Edward T., Janet Wilson James, Paul S. Boyer|title=Notable American Women: A Biographical Dictionary, Volume 5|publisher=Harvard University Press|page=414}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\n[[File:Newfsmastheadtr.png|thumb|150px|Former logo]]\nThe FSP is politically [[Trotskyism|Trotskyist]]. FSP leaders [[Clara Fraser]] (1923\u20131998) and Gloria Martin (1916\u20131995) built on the socialist analysis of women's [[oppression]] to create a [[Leninist]] party that is \"socialist-feminist\" in ideology and practice.<ref name=Love>{{cite book|last=Love|first=Barbara J.|title=Feminists Who Changed America, 1963-1975|url=https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=University of Illinois Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/feministswhochan00love/page/158 158]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ware|first=Susan|title=Notable American Women: A Biographical Dictionary, Volume 5: Completing the Twentieth Century|year=2005|publisher=Harvard University Press|pages=414\u2013415|author2=Stacy Braukman|chapter=Martin, Gloria}}</ref> The party views the liberation struggles of women, [[person of color|people of color]] and [[sexual minority|sexual minorities]] (such as [[homosexuality|gay people]]) as intrinsic to [[working class]] [[revolt]], and it looks to these specially-oppressed sectors of society to provide revolutionary leadership. Women comprise a predominant part of the party leadership. Overall, membership is very diverse and is composed of all genders and races. The party characterizes its ''National Comrades of Color Caucus'' as offering the party's diverse ranks of people of color an opportunity to work together as a team to grow as leaders and provide direction for the party's work in people of color movements.\n\n== Strategy ==\nThe party has frequently supported [[united front]] efforts on a number of issues and often helps other socialist groups get on the ballot, while simultaneously running its own candidates for office.\n\nThe United Front Against Fascism (UFAF)\u2014founded by the FSP, but also including a broad coalition of the [[left-wing politics|Left]], the [[LGBT]] community, [[trade union|labor unionists]], [[feminism|feminists]], [[people of color]], [[Jew]]s, and [[civil liberties|civil libertarians]]\u2014took the lead in mobilizing against [[neo-Nazism|neo-Nazis]] in the [[Pacific Northwest]] in the 1980s and 90s.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kubelbeck|first=Amy|title=Groups Of Gays Protest Picnic|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19900804&slug=1086045|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=Aug 4, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lacitis|first=Erik|title=An Ax To Grind -- When It Comes To Skinheads And Nazis, Loggers, Gays Unite|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910716&slug=1294655|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=1991-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Angelos|first=Constantine|title=Rice, Citizens Groups Join To Declare Seattle Won't Tolerate Hate Crimes|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19900519&slug=1072597|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=1990-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gough|first=William|title=A Gathering Of Neo-Nazis -- Encampment Draws Protest|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19911208&slug=1321657|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=Dec 8, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reang|first=Putsata|title=Supremacist Guilty In Klan Scuffle -- Federal Way Man Broke Free- Lancer's Camera|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19961002&slug=2352224|accessdate=2013-03-17|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=Oct 2, 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wilcox|first=Laird|title=The Cultic Milieu|year=2002|publisher=Rowman Altamira|pages=334\u2013335|editor=Jeffrey S. Kaplan, Hel\u00e9ne L\u00f6\u00f6w|chapter=Who Watches the Watchmen?}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seattle Freeway Hall.jpg|thumb|Freeway Hall in [[Seattle]]'s [[Northlake, Seattle, Washington|Northlake]] neighborhood was for many years the FSP headquarters.]]\nThe party has branches in a number of U.S. cities, as well as one in [[Melbourne, Australia]]. The ''Freedom Socialist'' newspaper is produced six times a year. Red Letter Press publishes books and pamphlets for the party. The FSP is affiliated with [[Radical Women]], which is an [[Autonomous entity|autonomous]] socialist feminist organization.\nIn 2003, Red Letter Press and its managing editor, Helen Gilbert, were the target of a complaint to the [[Federal Election Commission]] by the campaign committee of perennial presidential candidate [[Lyndon LaRouche]]. LaRouche alleged that Gilbert and the FSP publishing house, which had issued a pamphlet by Gilbert critical of LaRouche's ideology and political history,<ref>Helen Gilbert, [http://www.redletterpress.org/redreaders.html#larouche \"Lyndon Larouche: Fascism Restyled for the New Millennium\"], Redletterpress.org</ref> were in violation of campaign finance laws. The FEC found LaRouche's complaint to be without merit and dismissed it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/press/press2004/20041104mur.html|work=[[Federal Election Commission]]|title=COMPLIANCE CASE MADE PUBLIC|date=November 4, 2004|access-date=August 24, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831114409/http://fec.gov/press/press2004/20041104mur.html|archivedate=August 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Jordana Sardo, party organizer in Portland, Oregon, ran for the [[Oregon House of Representatives]] in Oregon's 45th House district, earning 8.74% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=97680%7celections |title=OR State House 45 Race - Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |access-date=2016-01-29}}</ref> Other FSP campaigns have been run in New York, Washington state, and California.<ref>Linda Averill, Freedom Socialist, October 1998, [http://www.socialism.com/drupal-6.8/?q=node/1224 \"Enthusiastic support puts radicals on the ballot in four states\"]</ref>\n\nIn [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]], the party ran a [[write-in]] presidential campaign with candidates [[Stephen Durham]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. president]] and Christina L\u00f3pez for [[Vice President of the United States|vice-president]].<ref>[http://votesocialism.com Durham/Lopez campaign website], Votesocialism.com</ref><ref>Ballot Access News, January 29, 2012, [http://www.ballot-access.org/2012/01/29/freedom-socialist-party-nominates-its-first-national-ticket/ \"Freedom Socialist Party Nominates its First National Ticket\"].</ref> The ticket received 117 votes nationwide.<ref>The Green Papers [http://www.thegreenpapers.com/G12/President-Details.phtml?n=DURHAM,STEPHENGAYLORD \"Votes for Stephen Gaylord Durham\"].</ref><ref>Ballot Access News [http://www.ballot-access.org/2012/12/31/new-york-state-posts-final-2012-election-returns-tally-presidential-vote-increases-by-400332-votes/ \"New York State Posts Final 2012 Election Returns Tally; Presidential Vote Increases by 400,332 Votes\"].</ref> Eight states do not permit write-in candidates, 32 require prior registration to be an official write-in, and many do not report write-ins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/2016-election/write-in-votes/|title=\"Planning to write in Paul Ryan or Bernie Sanders? It won\u2019t count in most states.\"|website=Washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 election, FSP critically endorsed [[Jeff Mackler]] of [[Socialist Action (United States)|Socialist Action]] for president.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://socialism.com/statement/this-year-of-the-detestable-election-exercise-your-democratic-rights-with-a-protest-vote/|title=This Year of the Detestable Election, exercise your democratic rights with a protest vote!|date=October 2016|website=Socialism.com|access-date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the party announced that member [[Steve Hoffman (activist)|Steve Hoffman]] would seek to petition onto the ballot for [[United States Senate election in Washington, 2018|United States Senate]] against incumbent Democrat [[Maria Cantwell]]. Hoffman got 7,390 votes (0,4%) and did not advance to the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialism.com/fs-article/union-stalwart-steve-hoffman-runs-us-senate-washington-state-freedom-socialist-party-campaign/|title=Union stalwart and socialist feminist Steve Hoffman runs for U.S. Senate|website=Freedom Socialist Party|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Socialism and Liberty Party]]\n* [[Party for Socialism and Liberation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.socialism.com/drupal-6.8/ Freedom Socialist Party]\n*[http://www.RedLetterPress.org Red Letter Press]\n*[http://www.RadicalWomen.org Radical Women]\n\n===Archives===\n*[http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=FreedomSocialistPartySeattleBranch1545.xml Freedom Socialist Party Seattle Branch Records.] 1984-1992. 3.14 cubic feet.\n*[http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=WindofferMelba1798.xml Melba Windoffer Papers.] 1933-1990. 7.42 cubic feet (8 boxes). Contains records from Windoffer's service with the Freedom Socialist Party.\n{{WashingtonPoliticalParties}}\n{{United States state and local political parties}}\n{{United 